            <pb facs="#TL-0429.jpg" n="part3_p037.jpg" xml:id="img_0037" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part3_p037.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_37_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>-/24-
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>potentalities, which are already in the child. Now if we look in this light to the Greek and the
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>Christian etucation, then we must say: the Greek—or as Kierkegaard has (nphasized), the Socratic
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>education, which he also called the Religion "A"—presupposes that every human being has
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>potentalities which only must be developed; in mythological terms Plato called this the historical
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>memory, which we find in every human being. The example he gives in the dialecte Menon
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>is the slave who is entirely uneducated but who can understand, in a very short time, the
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_37_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>Pythagorean proposition if it is shown to him; he has insight into it because, in mythological
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>isterns, he remember the mathematical structure and their inner evidence, from hismanpation
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>in the eternal ideas. If we take the word " memory" as a mythological /sic) away from this,
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>then we can speak, instead of that, in terms of man's essential nature, and can speak of the classes
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>concept of natural law, which means essential rational structure, which is always and essentially in
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>him and which only needs to be developed. whatever you give him, HE HeAS IT ALREADY.
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>You know that this meant, in Socratic metaphorism, the maientic art, the art of the midwifery,
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>of bringing out that which is in the htudent, and not necessarily in the teacher, by keeping him
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>to bring to light what he already has. This is the fundamental principle of all Socratic and,
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>I can add now, of the humanistic form of education.
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_37_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>There are two groups which do not accept this. The one are the miricists, or
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>positivists, who say that man is tabula rasa, and that experience mediated largely by theteacher, by
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>the history books, by the tradition, must be given to man from outside. Therefore you can form
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>sont
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>cʼest
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>décrier les
               <lb facs="#facs_37_tr_1_tl_14" n="N014"/>dʼune manière
